Five ways to boost retirement income
Here are the top tips to ensure your income at retirement meets your expectations.
3:01PM BST 24 Jun 2013
Fewer people are saving enough for retirement than they were at the peak of the recession, yet they expect double the income that they are likely to receive when they eventually stop work. Rock bottom interest rates, high inflation and poor investment returns have made it more difficult than ever to save enough for the future, but this hasn’t dampened our expectations for income in retirement. According to a report by insurer Scottish Widows, only 45pc of people are currently saving enough for their old age, compared to 54pc in 2009. Its research found that the average level of annual income people would feel comfortable living on at the age of 70 is £25,200. However, based on what people are actually saving, they are more likely to end up with an annual pension of only £3,860. This increases to £11,400 per year once the state pension is factored in, but is still 55pc less than the £25,200 annual income people are looking for. Andy James, advice policy manager, at wealth advice business Towry, said, "With annuity rates and other investment returns at all-time lows, it is questionable whether those even with wealth in excess of £500,000 would necessarily have sufficient to see them through a comfortable retirement. “At current rates, £500,000 used to purchase an annuity would be unlikely to provide more than £22,000 or so net of taxes, assuming a level income. While not leaving someone on the breadline, this is hardly going to put them in the lap of luxury.” However, there are ways to ensure your income doesn’t drop dramatically once you stop work. Here, we explore five different ways to maximise your income in retirement. 1. Choose the right annuity
Annuity rates have been hard hit by quantitative easing, which is effectively the creating of new money to stimulate the economy. As this money has focused on buying gilts, to which annuity rates are linked, this has forced up prices and so lowered their interest rates, reducing the income people can get from their pension savings. Although experts claim rates are likely to show signs of improvement soon, research from AXA Life Europe found that rates have declined by 29pc since the Bank of England began its quantitative easing programme. As a result, it is more important than ever that anyone planning on buying an annuity with their pension finds the best rate possible for them. Everyone has the right to exercise what is known as the ‘open market option’, which means you can use your pension fund to buy an annuity from any provider you want to. Remember to consider any health issues you may have, as this could result in a significant uplift in annuity rates, depending on the condition. If you do have any health problems, including being overweight, a smoker, or having high blood pressure, you may be eligible for an enhanced annuity which will provide you with a higher income than a conventional annuity. This is because your life expectancy is considered to be shorter than if you were in the peak of health. For more information about your annuity options call 0800 030 4693 or visit the Telegraph Retirement Planning Service, provided by Skipton Financial Services Limited 2. Consider drawdown
Those with pension funds of more than around £100,000 may want to consider drawdown, where they can start to take an income from their pension but, unlike an annuity, their money stays invested. Patrick Connolly, of IFAs AWD Chase de Vere, said, “This provides the opportunity to generate a higher level of income than an annuity over time if their investments perform well. There might also be scope to lock into a higher annuity rate in the future as you get older and if annuity rates increase. “However, drawdown is riskier than buying an annuity because your investments might perform poorly which could mean that you are forced to accept a lower level of income in the future. Those in drawdown should therefore regularly review their investment strategy, how their funds have performed, and the level of income they are taking.” 3. Review your savings and investments
As savings rates and investment returns have dropped in recent years, far fewer over-55s now receive an income from this source. According to Aviva’s Real Retirement report, three in ten people in this age group identified investments or savings as a source of income in May 2010, falling to 27pc in May last year and only 24pc in both December 2012 and May 2013. It’s not hard to understand why, especially as interest paid on most savings accounts is below the rate of inflation, even for cash Isas where all interest is tax-free. According to research by MoneySupermarket.com, currently no easy access accounts beat inflation, while there are just three fixed rate bonds and five fixed rate cash Isas that beat inflation. However, provided you are happy to accept a level of risk, you can increase your income by reducing the amount of cash you hold and reinvesting into other assets which are paying a higher level of income. Mr Connolly said, “Rather than investing in just equities or fixed interest, you should look to spread risks by investing into a combination of income producing assets. This can provide a more consistent level of income while hopefully also offering a reasonable level of capital protection. “Income investors shouldn’t just look at those asset classes or funds paying the most income as they are likely to take a high degree of risk in order to achieve a greater income"
Always seek professional financial advice to help you find the best investments to suit your individual circumstances.” For more information call the Telegraph Investment and Savings Service, provided by Skipton Financial Services Limited call 0800 121 4596
4. Release value from your property
Many people approaching retirement have the majority of their wealth tied up in their home. Research by Key Retirement Solutions, providers of The Telegraph Equity Release Service, found that pensioners own property worth almost £770bn, with 4.7 million retired householders owning their homes outright. One way to release some of this money is to downsize to a smaller property, although this may involve moving to a location or home which is less appealing than the one in which you currently live. Alternatively, you may want to consider retiring overseas, to a country where the cost of living may be lower than in the UK. However, for those who don’t want to move from their property, another option is equity release. These schemes involve releasing cash from your home, typically through either a lifetime mortgage or home reversion plan. A lifetime mortgage is a loan secured against your home. You don’t make regular repayments as the loan and interest are rolled up and usually repaid when you die or go into long-term care. A home reversion plan, however, allows you to release an amount of money by selling all or part of your home to a home reversion provider. You should always seek advice before opting for equity release as there are drawbacks. For example, take a cash lump sum and the costs involved will reduce the value of your estate and the amount of inheritance you will be able to leave, and may affect your tax position and welfare benefits. For more information call the Telegraph Equity Release Service, provided by Key Retirement Solutions Ltd on 0808 252 9087
5. Claim any help you may be entitled to
As much as £5.5bn of benefits goes unclaimed by pensioners, according to charity Age UK. It claims that older people often miss out because they think the application process is too complicated, or because they don’t think they will qualify. If you are on a low income you may be eligible for the guarantee element of Pension Credit, which tops up your income to at least £145.40 per week for single people and £222.05 for couples. You may also be able to get the savings element of the pension credit, worth up to £18.06 per week for single people or £22.89 for couples. While there is no upper savings limit to qualify pension credit, if you have savings of more than £6,000 the benefits are reduced. Annuity Calculator - Work out how much retirement income you may receive from your personal pensions with our handy annuity calculator. For more information about your annuity options or to request a free guide call 0800 030 4693. Telegraph retirement planning service
