Katharine Welby: 'I got to the point where I just couldn’t bear the thought of living any more'
Katharine Welby, daughter of the Archbishop of Canterbury, speaks for the first time about her battle with depression
By Cole Moreton
7:00AM BST 05 May 2013
Follow Comments
When the news broke that her father was about to be appointed Archbishop of Canterbury, Katharine Welby found herself in floods of tears. “I ended up crying and crying,” she says, but not because she didn’t want her dad to get the job. “I was excited for him and for what he could do for the Church,” she says, although she was also “scared” by the impact it would have on her life and that of the whole family. But that wasn’t the reason for the tears. “I was overwhelmed. My head is permanently full at the moment. There isn’t very much leeway. It gets to a point where it is too full. I cease being able to function.”
Her weeping was caused by depression. The illness is “a constant struggle” in her life and creates moments of crisis in which she wants to “run away and hide in a hole”. In the past, it has brought her to the brink of suicide. Related Articles
Welby: 'I found religion boring'
13 May 2013
New Archbishop's daughter jokes his election is 'corrupt'
04 Feb 2013
Archbishop of Canterbury's daughter: My battle with depression
23 Apr 2013
And it left her unable to cope with the emotional overload last November, as the rest of the world found out what she already knew but was not allowed to tell: that her father had been chosen as the new head of the Church of England, spiritual leader to nearly 80 million people around the planet. “That is a terrifying thought,” she says with a little laugh. “Especially if you know my dad. No, he’s a wonderful man.”
She clearly loves and admires him very much. She is also evidently nervous, smoothing her skirt repeatedly at first as we sit together in an office in east London. The nerves are understandable, given that what she wants to say is both intimate and revealing. This pale, petite 26-year-old with a skittish sense of humour and a distracted smile is trying to make sense of the realisation that an awful lot of people want to know about her private struggles, after the extraordinary reaction to a blog entry she wrote last month. Meant to be read by a few friends, it provoked headlines and news reports around the world. Katharine Welby, daughter of the Archbishop of Canterbury, Justin Welby (GEOFF PUGH)
“I have depression,” she wrote. “I get it quite badly on a regular basis and kind of cry and get tired and just generally see no hope in the world.” The chemicals in her brain seemed to be at war with her circumstances, she wrote. “I have friends, a nice home, a very supportive family nearby, a good church, a good job, a brilliant doctor and an incredibly wonderful boyfriend. However, previously I have had many of these things and still found myself unable to find a way out of the despair.” Faith had helped her find hope, she wrote, even though Christians often failed to support or understand people with depression. Did she really think the media would not pick up on such an honest, moving confession, with its challenge to the Church? After all, she had already been in the papers for tweeting a picture of herself in a tea cosy that happened to look very like a mitre, just before a fiercely contested vote on women bishops. “I was like, ‘Oops. Sorry. Shouldn’t have done that’,” she says of the tweet now, laughing. The blog showed another side to her, and this time she showed it to her father, who warned it would get picked up. “In the past, that has meant one or two people getting in touch to ask if I would like to talk to them, to which I have always said no. I said to him, ‘You didn’t tell me it would go viral, that’s not fair!’”
Faced with a flood of interview requests, she found allies in Time to Change, a campaign led by the charities Mind and Rethink Mental Illness, which seeks to fight the stigma and discrimination around mental-health problems. This is the only interview she has given. “It is a scary and intimidating thing: I am worried about getting boxed up as the Archbishop of Canterbury’s Depressed Daughter.” Does she regret writing the blog then? “No, I am glad I did it because the reaction I got was so huge and encouraging, loving and generous. I had a massive sense of relief.” Most of the hundreds of emails and tweets she received thanked her for speaking out. Today, on home territory, dressed in businesslike black leggings and a black top with a fuchsia skirt that offsets her striking red hair, she is able to overcome the nerves and begin to tell her story. It starts in 1986. Born in London, she grew up in Durham, then various parishes in Warwickshire, and the city of Coventry. Depression began to make an impact while she was studying for A-levels. “I found that I wasn’t quite living in the world. Wherever possible, I was escaping. I was buying four or five DVDs a week and spending all my time watching them or reading books. Life was just a bit too much. I closed down to what was happening around me.”
Things came to a head after her first year reading theology at Manchester University. “I couldn’t really work, I was miserable. It was a relief to be told I was depressed. The doctor said, ‘Get help now and catch it before it gets bad’. So obviously, I just ignored that and didn’t go and get any help...”
She’s funny, in a dry, self-deprecating way. The depression came back after her degree. “It got really bad, but this time a doctor called me a hypochondriac.” She started having counselling, moved to London and joined the police force, believing everything would be OK. “I wanted to make a difference. I do believe in justice.”
For three years she patrolled in Hackney, one of the toughest beats in the country. “I’m a tiny person, so I’ve always been a bit more feisty than people expect, just to show them. I might be tiny but I can fight you. In a totally non-violent sort of way…” She laughs again, but the things she saw in the police were brutal. Women battered by their husbands, children pressed into becoming “revolting” members of gun gangs, and decomposing bodies. “I dealt with a lot of sudden deaths,” she says. “The first I ever saw was in a hostel. He was in his Seventies. Nobody knew anything about him. You couldn’t tell what smelt worse: the milk and steak he had left out of the fridge before dying, or him. He was skin and bone. A tiny little man. The idea that someone could die and no one would even know until the flies arrived… that’s devastating.”
She found the work exhausting, emotionally. “I couldn’t give enough to people. The police are not here to heal the wounds of society, they are here to hold the line. I wanted to make society better.” The depression surged again at the beginning of last year, with what she calls “catastrophic” results. “I did not like being me. I hated it. I was exhausted by it. I wanted to be someone else. Or nowhere else.” Was she suicidal? “Not quite. That came in April. My boyfriend broke up with me. That was the final straw. I didn’t have the space I needed in my head to grieve for this relationship. My head was already full of things that were hurting.” She went off sick. “My whole life fell apart. What was happening reminded me how worthless I was, how no one wanted me, how much of a burden I was. All of these underlying things I had believed for a long time but ignored. I got to the point where I just couldn’t bear the thought of living any more. That got very aggressive and all-consuming.”
She knew enough by now to act against it. “I would go out every day, which was often the most horrendous effort, but I knew that if I didn’t then I would get myself into some real trouble,” she says. “When I completely lose it, I do get very erratic and just try to harm myself in any way possible. I knew that if I left myself alone for days at a time I would be a serious danger to myself. So I had a few very good friends I could just go and sit with.”
They let her know they cared, however much she withdrew. Her parents were in Durham, where her father was bishop. Did they know? “I hid it from them quite well. I don’t want to put a burden on other people – which in a way is quite selfish, because you’re actually giving people no opportunity to love you back to health. They found out in the summer when I went to stay with them. My weight had dropped drastically. I was down to seven stone.” How, then, did she begin to recover? “I spent hours every day reading the Bible and praying. I had Post-it notes with encouraging verses written on them and I stuck them all over my room. Everywhere. I got to the point where I was so miserable in myself, but so happy and peaceful with God.” She was also helped by a “fantastic” doctor who listened, understood and eventually found the right medication. “I had cognitive behavioural therapy for a while. That helped. I had very good friends. I moved to a church where you are noticed and included immediately.”
What is her experience of the Church failing people with depression? “Some Christians will say, ‘You’re not depressed’. Then they insinuate – or state directly – that you don’t have enough faith, or that depression is not biblical because the Holy Spirit gives us joy, or that you haven’t experienced the love of God. To which I just say, ‘I experienced the love of God more during my darkest period than at any other point in my life.’” In the autumn, she began to work with Livability, a charity that supports disabled adults and children, enabling them to live as independently as possible. She co-ordinates a team of community workers and engages with social media on behalf of the charity. “I am able to work now because it is a very clear routine,” she says. “I get up at a certain time, have my shower, do my hair, do my make-up, have my breakfast with a cup of tea, read my Bible, do my journal, go to work, come home from work, do something in the evening and go to bed. It is very clear and distinct. That keeps me going. But I have so many ups and downs.”
She has the support of a boyfriend called Mike, who is an IT consultant. “I have been afraid of telling boyfriends in the past about the depression, because of a couple who couldn’t deal with it. It is great when you do find someone who understands that it is not who you are but an add-on. Then the fear evaporates, because they do just love you for what you are.”
As life began to improve, she was able to shrug off speculation about her father getting Canterbury. He had only been a bishop for a year, after all. “It seemed ridiculous,” she says. “Right the way up to when he called me and said, ‘Katharine, I’ve got an interview.’” What was her reaction? “I was like [shouting]: ‘What? No! You said this would never happen in a million years. Seriously? If you’re going to say no, then you’ve got to mean no. I don’t understand!’ ”
Her laughter is infectious. How did she feel when she’d had a chance to calm down? “Partly, I was really excited. I am biased, I am his daughter, but my dad is a brilliant man. He is an extraordinary man, of grace and humility but also authority, which is a very rare combination.” Only partly? “I had a mixed reaction – I was very excited and very scared.” So far, the Welbys are surviving a level of scrutiny that would make the Camerons call for Special Branch. But Katharine has some decisions to make, in the wake of the fuss about her blog. “People work for years to get a profile and it just got landed on me. It feels like, ‘This is rude. I should just keep my head down’. But at the same time, I’m not naturally good at that,” she says. “I do want to say what I want to say. I care passionately about the fact that people with mental problems or any form of disadvantage are excluded. This isn’t good enough. God created everyone. We are all designed in his image. That’s true of a person with autism, a person with cerebral palsy, a person in a wheelchair, a man, a woman. Every single person can give a glimpse of God.” She doesn’t know if her depression is inherited, and doesn’t particularly care. “Hopefully, one day I will be able to live free of it, and happily so. Maybe I won’t. But we have to acknowledge it is a very real thing, which affects a huge number of people,” she says. “These people need support and they need love, and they need to know that if they have to retreat into a dark hole, someone might text them and say, ‘Hey, thinking of you’. Or drop in with a stew, so they can eat. Whatever it is, a sign that someone is thinking about them. “I know from personal experience that when you withdraw, you are often desperate for someone to reach out to you. If that’s all the rest of us can offer, it’s a start.”
